JDBCProvider.description: One-phase commit DB2 JCC provider that supports JDBC 3.0. Data sources that use this provider support only 1-phase commit processing, unless you use driver type 2 with the application server for z/OS. If you use the application server for z/OS, driver type 2 uses RRS and supports 2-phase commit processing.
JDBCProvider.name: DB2 Universal JDBC Driver Provider

J2EEResourceProperty.description: JDBC driver property: activateDatabase
J2EEResourceProperty.name: activateDatabase

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Specifies the database names for alternative data sharing groups to which an application can connect.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: alternateGroupDatabaseName

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Specifies the port numbers for alternative data sharing groups to which an application can connect.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: alternateGroupPortNumber

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Specifies the host names for alternative data sharing groups to which an application can connect.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: alternateGroupServerName

J2EEResourceProperty.description: If beginTranForResultSetScrollingAPIs is enabled, the application server attempts to begin a transaction or enlist in a transaction when the connection is not currently enlisted in a transaction and a result set scrolling operation is performed.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: beginTranForResultSetScrollingAPIs

J2EEResourceProperty.description: If beginTranForVendorAPIs is enabled, the application server attempts to begin a transaction or enlist in a transaction when the connection is not currently enlisted in a transaction and a vendor API is invoked with the wrapper pattern or with WSCallHelper.jdbcCall or WSCallHelper.jdbcPass.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: beginTranForVendorAPIs

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Indicates the schema of the DB2 shadow catalog tables or views to search when you issue a database meta data catalog query.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: cliSchema

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Specifies accounting information for the current client for the connection. This information is for client accounting purposes. This value can change during a connection. For a DB2 UDB for Linux, UNIX and Windows server, the maximum length is 255 bytes. A Java empty string is valid for this value, but a Java null value is not valid.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: clientAccountingInformation

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Specifies application information for the current client for the connection. This information is for client accounting purposes. This value can change during a connection. For a DB2 UDB for Linux, UNIX and Windows server, the maximum length is 255 bytes. A Java empty string is valid for this value, but a Java null value is not valid.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: clientApplicationInformation

J2EEResourceProperty.description: The list of alternate server port(s) for the DB2 server. If more than one alternate server port is specified, then the ports must be separated by a comma. For example, 5000,50001.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: clientRerouteAlternatePortNumber

J2EEResourceProperty.description: The list of alternate server name(s) for the DB2 server. If more than one alternate server name is specified, then the names must be separated by a comma. For example, host1,host2.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: clientRerouteAlternateServerName

J2EEResourceProperty.description: The name used to bind the DB2 client reroute server list to JNDI name space.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: clientRerouteServerListJNDIName

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Specifies the current client user name for the connection. This information is for client accounting purposes. Unlike the JDBC connection user name, this value can change during a connection. For a DB2 UDB for Linux, UNIX and Windows server, the maximum length is 255 bytes.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: clientUser

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Specifies the workstation name for the current client for the connection. This information is for client accounting purposes. This value can change during a connection. For a DB2 UDB for Linux, UNIX and Windows server, the maximum length is 255 bytes. A Java empty string is valid for this value, but a Java null value is not valid.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: clientWorkstation

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Deprecated. Please use the validateNewConnectionRetryCount property instead. This is useful only if dbFailOverEnabled flag is true. This property controls how many times WebSphere will try to get a connection from the database before giving up
J2EEResourceProperty.name: connRetriesDuringDBFailover

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Deprecated. Please use the validateNewConnectionRetryInterval instead. This is useful only if dbFailOverEnabled flag is true. This property controls the interval between retries to retrieve a connection from the database.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: connRetryIntervalDuringDBFailover

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Specifies whether the IBM Data Server Driver for JDBC and SQLJ throws an SQLException or rolls back a transaction without throwing an SQLException when a connection is closed in the middle of the transaction.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: connectionCloseWithInFlightTransaction

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Determines whether connections are shared based on the current state of the connection (-1) or the original connection request (0). To specify with greater granularity which connection properties are matched based on the current state, you may combine the following constants by adding them together: 1=transaction isolation level, 2=read only, 4=holdability, 8=type map, 16=catalog.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: connectionSharing

J2EEResourceProperty.description: JDBC driver property: currentAlternateGroupEntry
J2EEResourceProperty.name: currentAlternateGroupEntry

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Specifies the value for the CURRENT FUNCTION PATH special register of the DB2 server.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: currentFunctionPath

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Specifies a comma-separated list of collections on the server. If this property is specified, the currentPackageSet property is ignored.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: currentPackagePath

J2EEResourceProperty.description: This property is used in conjunction with the DB2Binder - collection option which is given when the JDBC/CLI packageset is bound during installation by the DBA.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: currentPackageSet

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Specifies the default schema name that is used to qualify unqualified database objects in dynamically prepared SQL statements. This value of this property sets the value in the CURRENT SQLID special register on a DB2 UDB for OS/390 or z/OS server. If the currentSQLID property is not set, the default schema name is the value in the CURRENT SQLID special register.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: currentSQLID

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Identifies the default schema name used to qualify unqualified database object references where applicable in dynamically prepared SQL statements. Unless currentSchema is used, the default schema name is the authorization id of the current session user.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: currentSchema

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Specifies whether java.sql.ResultSet.TYPE_SCROLL_SENSITIVE maps to sensitive dynamic or sensitive static scroll. This property is ignored for insensitive scrollable cursors. The default is 0 (TYPE_SCROLL_SENSITIVE_STATIC). Alternatively, it can be set to 1 (TYPE_SCROLL_SENSITIVE_DYNAMIC) to have TYPE_SCROLL_SENSITIVE cursors map to sensitive dynamic cursors or set to 2 (TYPE_SCROLL_ASENSITIVE) to use SENSITIVE whenever possible, otherwise, fallback to INSENSITIVE when the request doesn't support SENSITIVE.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: cursorSensitivity

J2EEResourceProperty.description: This is a required property. This is an actual database name, and its not the locally catalogued database name. The Universal JDBC Driver does not rely on information catalogued in the DB2 database directory.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: databaseName

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Deprecated. Please use the validateNewConnection property instead. This flag should be set to true only if the backend database is configured with failover capability. This flag will indicate to WebSphere to validate connections when they first get created and to keep trying to get a good connection from the database when the validation fails.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: dbFailOverEnabled

J2EEResourceProperty.description: This property provides a performance directive that affects the internal semantics of the input data type conversion capability of the driver. By default the Universal driver defers 'internal prepare requests'. In this case, the driver works without the benefit of described parameter or result set meta data until execute time. So undescsribed input data is sent 'as is' to the server without any data type cross-conversation of the inputs.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: deferPrepares

J2EEResourceProperty.description: The description of this datasource.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: description

J2EEResourceProperty.description: The JDBC connectivity-type of a data source. If you want to use type 4 driver, set the value to 4. If you want to use type 2 driver, set the value to 2. On WebSphere Application Server for Z/OS, driverType 2 uses RRS and supports 2-phase commit processing.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: driverType

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Specifies whether failover to an alternate group is seamless or non-seamless.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: enableAlternateGroupSeamlessACR

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Specifies whether the IBM Data Server Driver for JDBC and SQLJ enables client affinities for cascaded failover support. Possible values are: 1 (enabled), 2 (disabled). Disabled is the default when no value is specified.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: enableClientAffinitiesList

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Enables the implicit passing of client information on database connections. The client information provided on each connection is the same as for the WAS.clientinfo trace group. Whereas the WAS.clientinfo trace is configured on an application server, the enableClientInformation property applies to a data source configuration.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: enableClientInformation

J2EEResourceProperty.description: JDBC driver property: enableExtendedDescribe
J2EEResourceProperty.name: enableExtendedDescribe

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Enables the use of default and unassigned indicators as parameters.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: enableExtendedIndicators

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Indicates whether or not to detect multithreaded access to a Connection and its corresponding Statements, ResultSets, and MetaDatas.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: enableMultithreadedAccessDetection

J2EEResourceProperty.description: The error detection model determines how fatal connection and statement errors are detected, including which types of exceptions are raised to the application. Under the ExceptionChecking model, the application server uses the error mapping facility defined in the Data Store Helper only to identify errors. The application server does not replace exceptions thrown by the JDBC driver with exceptions defined in the error map of the Data Store Helper. Under the ExceptionMapping model, the application server uses the error mapping facility defined in the Data Store Helper to detect fatal connection and statement errors. The application server overrides exceptions thrown by the JDBC driver with exceptions defined in the error map of the Data Store Helper. The ExceptionMapping setting is not compliant with JDBC 4.0 and above, but is necessary for applications written according to the WebSphere Application Server exception mapping model.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: errorDetectionModel

J2EEResourceProperty.description: JDBC driver property: fullyMaterializeInputStreamsOnBatchExecution
J2EEResourceProperty.name: fullyMaterializeInputStreamsOnBatchExecution

J2EEResourceProperty.description: This setting can affect whether LOB data is fully materialized in the JDBC driver when a row is fetched, or whether LOB data is retrieved in pieces as needed. The actual behavior depends on whether the database server supports progressive streaming. Please refer to DB2 documentation for this property. The default value is true.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: fullyMaterializeLobData

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Specifies the actions that the IBM Data Server Driver for JDBC and SQLJ takes when a transaction encounters a deadlock or a timeout.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: implicitRollbackOption

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Specifies the behavior of the IBM Data Server Driver for JDBC and SQLJ when an application calls the Statement.cancel method.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: interruptProcessingMode

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Specifies whether to allow JMS to get optimized connections from this datasource. This option will prevent JDBC Applications from getting connections.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: jmsOnePhaseOptimization

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Specifies the maximum time in seconds before an unresponsive connection is detected as no longer alive.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: keepAliveTimeOut

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Determines whether DB2 keeps dynamic SQL statements after commit points. This is applicable only when the target server is DB2 for z/OS. The property default depends on the server. Specifying 1 means YES, DB2 keeps dynamic SQL statements after commit points. Specifying 2 means NO, DB2 does not keep dynamic SQL statements after commit points. If this property is not set defaults are assumed. If the JDBC package set is custom bound without these defaults, this property must be set. The driver has no way to know how custom JDBC packages were bound under current DRDA architecture. This property is not a directive to server, but rather a driver directive.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: keepDynamic

J2EEResourceProperty.description: For a data source that uses Kerberos security, specifies the name that is used for the data source when it is registered with the Kerberos Key Distribution Center (KDC). It should be of the format user@realm.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: kerberosServerPrincipal

J2EEResourceProperty.description: The maximum time in seconds to wait for the DataSource object to connect to a data source. A value of 0 means that the timeout value is the default system timeout value.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: loginTimeout

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Specifies the maximum size of an internal buffer that is used for caching input parameter values for PreparedStatement objects.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: maxConnCachedParamBufferSize

J2EEResourceProperty.description: The maximum number of connection retries attempted by automatic client reroute if the primary connection to the server fails. This property is only used if the retryIntervalClientReroute property is also set.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: maxRetriesForClientReroute

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Setting this flag to true will cause the Application Server to never enlist the connections from this datasource in global or local transactions. Applications must explicitly call setAutoCommit(false) on the connection if they want to start a local transaction on the connection and they must commit or rollback the transaction that they started.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: nonTransactionalDataSource

J2EEResourceProperty.description: The TCP/IP port number where the DRDA server resides. If custom property driverType is set to 4, this property is required.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: portNumber

J2EEResourceProperty.description: This SQL statement is used for pre-test connection function. For example, SELECT 1 FROM [TESTTABLE]. If pre-testing of connection is enabled for the connection pool, this SQL statement will be executed to the connection to make sure the connection is good. If you leave this field blank, the default SQL statement, SELECT CURRENT SQLID FROM SYSIBM.SYSDUMMY1, will be used at runtime. This will slow down the execution because of the exception handling if table SYSIBM.SYSDUMMY1 is not defined in the database. Users are recommended to provide their own SQL statement to improve the performance.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: preTestSQLString

J2EEResourceProperty.description: JDBC driver property: profileName
J2EEResourceProperty.name: profileName

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Specifies whether the JDBC driver uses progressive streaming when progressive streaming is supported on the data source. Valid values are DB2BaseDataSource.YES (1) and DB2BaseDataSource.NO (2). The default value is DB2BaseDataSource.NOT_SET (0). Please refer to DB2 documentation for this property.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: progressiveStreaming

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Enable the propagation of client identity using DB2 Trusted Context. The resource reference must be configured with trusted connections authentication for this setting to take affect.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: propagateClientIdentityUsingTrustedContext

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Specifies whether the IBM Data Server Driver for JDBC and SQLJ cancels the SQL statement or closes the underlying connection when the query timeout interval for a Statement object expires.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: queryTimeoutInterruptProcessingMode

J2EEResourceProperty.description: This property creates a read only connection. By default this value is false.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: readOnly

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Specifies whether to allow reauthentication of connections. This option requires implementation of the doConnectionSetupPerTransaction() method on the DataStoreHelper where the reauthentication is expected to take place.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: reauthentication

J2EEResourceProperty.description: JDBC driver property: recordTemporalHistory
J2EEResourceProperty.name: recordTemporalHistory

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Determine whether ResultSets are closed or kept open when committing a transaction. The possible values are: 1 (HOLD_CURSORS_OVER_COMMIT), 2 (CLOSE_CURSORS_AT_COMMIT).
J2EEResourceProperty.name: resultSetHoldability

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Directs all calls to the standard JDBC SQLException.getMessage() to invoke a server-side stored procedure which retrieves the readable message text for the error.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: retrieveMessagesFromServerOnGetMessage

J2EEResourceProperty.description: The amount of time (in seconds) between automatic client reroute retries. This property is only used if the maxRetriesForClientReroute property is also set.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: retryIntervalForClientReroute

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Specifies the DRDA security mechanism. Possible values are: 3 (CLEAR_TEXT_PASSWORD_SECURITY), 4 (USER_ONLY_SECURITY), 7 (ENCRYPTED_PASSWORD_SECURITY), 9 (ENCRYPTED_USER_AND_PASSWORD_SECURITY), or 11 (KERBEROS_SECURITY). Plesae refer to DB2 manual for the constant value. If this property is specified, the specified security mechanism is the only mechanism that is used. If no value is specified for this property, 3 is used.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: securityMechanism

J2EEResourceProperty.description: The TCP/IP address or host name for the DRDA server. If custom property driverType is set to 4, this property is required.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: serverName

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Sets the time zone at session level on the server.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: sessionTimeZone

J2EEResourceProperty.description: JDBC driver property: sqljCloseStmtsWithOpenResultSet
J2EEResourceProperty.name: sqljCloseStmtsWithOpenResultSet

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Specifies whether the IBM DB2 Driver for JDBC and SQLJ allows using and loading of SQLJ profiles with the same Java name in multiple J2EE application (.ear) files.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: sqljEnableClassLoaderSpecificProfiles

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Specifies whether the IBM Data Server Driver for JDBC and SQLJ removes trailing zeroes when it retrieves data from a DECFLOAT, DECIMAL, or NUMERIC column as a java.math.BigDecimal object.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: stripTrailingZerosForDecimalNumbers

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Use the time remaining (if any) in a JTA transaction as the default query timeout for SQL statements. This feature depends on JDBC driver and database support for java.sql.Statement.setQueryTimeout. For DB2 type 2 on z/OS, the following data source properties impact support for query timeout: interruptProcessingMode, queryTimeoutInterruptProcessingMode. Refer to the JDBC driver documentation for more information.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: syncQueryTimeoutWithTransactionTimeout

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Specifies the level at which the IBM Data Server Driver for JDBC and SQLJ creates a java.util.Timer object for waiting for query execution to time out.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: timerLevelForQueryTimeOut

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Specifies the directory where the trace file will be created.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: traceDirectory

J2EEResourceProperty.description: The trace file to store the trace output. If you specify the trace file, the DB2 Jcc trace will be logged in this trace file. If this property is not specified and the WAS.database trace group is enabled, then both WebSphere trace and DB2 trace will be logged into the WebSphere trace file.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: traceFile

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Specifies whether to append to or overwrite the file that is specified by the traceFile property. The default is false, which means that the file that is specified by the traceFile property is overwritten.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: traceFileAppend

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Specifies the maximum number of trace files, for circular tracing.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: traceFileCount

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Specifies the maximum size of each trace file, for circular tracing.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: traceFileSize

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Specifies the level of trace, determined by a bitwise combination of constants: TRACE_NONE=0, TRACE_CONNECTION_CALLS=1, TRACE_STATEMENT_CALLS=2, TRACE_RESULT_SET_CALLS=4, TRACE_DRIVER_CONFIGURATION=16, TRACE_CONNECTS=32, TRACE_DRDA_FLOWS=64, TRACE_RESULT_SET_META_DATA=128, TRACE_PARAMETER_META_DATA=256, TRACE_DIAGNOSTICS=512, TRACE_SQLJ=1024, TRACE_META_CALLS=8192, TRACE_DATASOURCE_CALLS=16384, TRACE_LARGE_OBJECT_CALLS=32768, TRACE_SYSTEM_MONITOR=131072, TRACE_TRACEPOINTS=262144, TRACE_ALL=-1.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: traceLevel

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Specifies whether sequential tracing or circular tracing is done.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: traceOption

J2EEResourceProperty.description: JDBC driver property: translateForBitData
J2EEResourceProperty.name: translateForBitData

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Used with testConnection only. When set to true, clientRerouteServerListJNDIName will be unbound from JNDI name space when performing testConnection.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: unbindClientRerouteListFromJndi

J2EEResourceProperty.description: JDBC driver property: updateCountForBatch
J2EEResourceProperty.name: updateCountForBatch

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Specifies whether the IBM Data Server Driver for JDBC and SQLJ uses only the SQL built-in function IDENTITY_VAL_LOCAL to determine automatically generated key values.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: useIdentityValLocalForAutoGeneratedKeys

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Configure this property if your backend uses the Database Partitioning Feature (DPF) and your partitioning key remains constant throughout a transaction
J2EEResourceProperty.name: useTransactionRedirect

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Overlays existing entries in the error map by invoking DataStoreHelper.setUserDefinedMap. The userDefinedErrorMap can be used to add, change, or remove entries from the error map. Entries are delimited by ; (semicolon). Each entry consists of a key and value, where the key is an error code (numeric value) or SQLState (text enclosed in double quotes). Keys and values are are separated by = (equals sign). For example, to remove the mapping of SQLState S1000, add a mapping of error code 1062 to DuplicateKeyException, and add a mapping of SQLState 08004 to StaleConnectionException, the following can be specified for userDefinedErrorMap: "S1000"=;1062=com.ibm.websphere.ce.cm.DuplicateKeyException;"08004"=com.ibm.websphere.ce.cm.StaleConnectionException
J2EEResourceProperty.name: userDefinedErrorMap

J2EEResourceProperty.description: The JDBC connectivity-type of a data source. If you want to use type 4 driver, set the value to 4. If you want to use type 2 driver, set the value to 2. On WebSphere Application Server for Z/OS, driverType 2 uses RRS and supports 2-phase commit processing.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: driverType

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Specifies whether failover to an alternate group is seamless or non-seamless.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: enableAlternateGroupSeamlessACR

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Specifies whether the IBM Data Server Driver for JDBC and SQLJ enables client affinities for cascaded failover support. Possible values are: 1 (enabled), 2 (disabled). Disabled is the default when no value is specified.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: enableClientAffinitiesList

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Enables the implicit passing of client information on database connections. The client information provided on each connection is the same as for the WAS.clientinfo trace group. Whereas the WAS.clientinfo trace is configured on an application server, the enableClientInformation property applies to a data source configuration.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: enableClientInformation

J2EEResourceProperty.description: JDBC driver property: enableExtendedDescribe
J2EEResourceProperty.name: enableExtendedDescribe

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Enables the use of default and unassigned indicators as parameters.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: enableExtendedIndicators

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Indicates whether or not to detect multithreaded access to a Connection and its corresponding Statements, ResultSets, and MetaDatas.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: enableMultithreadedAccessDetection

J2EEResourceProperty.description: The error detection model determines how fatal connection and statement errors are detected, including which types of exceptions are raised to the application. Under the ExceptionChecking model, the application server uses the error mapping facility defined in the Data Store Helper only to identify errors. The application server does not replace exceptions thrown by the JDBC driver with exceptions defined in the error map of the Data Store Helper. Under the ExceptionMapping model, the application server uses the error mapping facility defined in the Data Store Helper to detect fatal connection and statement errors. The application server overrides exceptions thrown by the JDBC driver with exceptions defined in the error map of the Data Store Helper. The ExceptionMapping setting is not compliant with JDBC 4.0 and above, but is necessary for applications written according to the WebSphere Application Server exception mapping model.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: errorDetectionModel

J2EEResourceProperty.description: JDBC driver property: fullyMaterializeInputStreamsOnBatchExecution
J2EEResourceProperty.name: fullyMaterializeInputStreamsOnBatchExecution

J2EEResourceProperty.description: This setting can affect whether LOB data is fully materialized in the JDBC driver when a row is fetched, or whether LOB data is retrieved in pieces as needed. The actual behavior depends on whether the database server supports progressive streaming. Please refer to DB2 documentation for this property. The default value is true.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: fullyMaterializeLobData

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Specifies the actions that the IBM Data Server Driver for JDBC and SQLJ takes when a transaction encounters a deadlock or a timeout.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: implicitRollbackOption

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Specifies the behavior of the IBM Data Server Driver for JDBC and SQLJ when an application calls the Statement.cancel method.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: interruptProcessingMode

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Specifies whether to allow JMS to get optimized connections from this datasource. This option will prevent JDBC Applications from getting connections.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: jmsOnePhaseOptimization

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Specifies the maximum time in seconds before an unresponsive connection is detected as no longer alive.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: keepAliveTimeOut

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Determines whether DB2 keeps dynamic SQL statements after commit points. This is applicable only when the target server is DB2 for z/OS. The property default depends on the server. Specifying 1 means YES, DB2 keeps dynamic SQL statements after commit points. Specifying 2 means NO, DB2 does not keep dynamic SQL statements after commit points. If this property is not set defaults are assumed. If the JDBC package set is custom bound without these defaults, this property must be set. The driver has no way to know how custom JDBC packages were bound under current DRDA architecture. This property is not a directive to server, but rather a driver directive.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: keepDynamic

J2EEResourceProperty.description: For a data source that uses Kerberos security, specifies the name that is used for the data source when it is registered with the Kerberos Key Distribution Center (KDC). It should be of the format user@realm.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: kerberosServerPrincipal

J2EEResourceProperty.description: The maximum time in seconds to wait for the DataSource object to connect to a data source. A value of 0 means that the timeout value is the default system timeout value.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: loginTimeout

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Specifies the maximum size of an internal buffer that is used for caching input parameter values for PreparedStatement objects.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: maxConnCachedParamBufferSize

J2EEResourceProperty.description: The maximum number of connection retries attempted by automatic client reroute if the primary connection to the server fails. This property is only used if the retryIntervalClientReroute property is also set.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: maxRetriesForClientReroute

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Setting this flag to true will cause the Application Server to never enlist the connections from this datasource in global or local transactions. Applications must explicitly call setAutoCommit(false) on the connection if they want to start a local transaction on the connection and they must commit or rollback the transaction that they started.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: nonTransactionalDataSource

J2EEResourceProperty.description: The TCP/IP port number where the DRDA server resides. If custom property driverType is set to 4, this property is required.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: portNumber

J2EEResourceProperty.description: This SQL statement is used for pre-test connection function. For example, SELECT 1 FROM [TESTTABLE]. If pre-testing of connection is enabled for the connection pool, this SQL statement will be executed to the connection to make sure the connection is good. If you leave this field blank, the default SQL statement, SELECT CURRENT SQLID FROM SYSIBM.SYSDUMMY1, will be used at runtime. This will slow down the execution because of the exception handling if table SYSIBM.SYSDUMMY1 is not defined in the database. Users are recommended to provide their own SQL statement to improve the performance.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: preTestSQLString

J2EEResourceProperty.description: JDBC driver property: profileName
J2EEResourceProperty.name: profileName

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Specifies whether the JDBC driver uses progressive streaming when progressive streaming is supported on the data source. Valid values are DB2BaseDataSource.YES (1) and DB2BaseDataSource.NO (2). The default value is DB2BaseDataSource.NOT_SET (0). Please refer to DB2 documentation for this property.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: progressiveStreaming

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Enable the propagation of client identity using DB2 Trusted Context. The resource reference must be configured with trusted connections authentication for this setting to take affect.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: propagateClientIdentityUsingTrustedContext

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Specifies whether the IBM Data Server Driver for JDBC and SQLJ cancels the SQL statement or closes the underlying connection when the query timeout interval for a Statement object expires.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: queryTimeoutInterruptProcessingMode

J2EEResourceProperty.description: This property creates a read only connection. By default this value is false.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: readOnly

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Specifies whether to allow reauthentication of connections. This option requires implementation of the doConnectionSetupPerTransaction() method on the DataStoreHelper where the reauthentication is expected to take place.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: reauthentication

J2EEResourceProperty.description: JDBC driver property: recordTemporalHistory
J2EEResourceProperty.name: recordTemporalHistory

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Determine whether ResultSets are closed or kept open when committing a transaction. The possible values are: 1 (HOLD_CURSORS_OVER_COMMIT), 2 (CLOSE_CURSORS_AT_COMMIT).
J2EEResourceProperty.name: resultSetHoldability

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Directs all calls to the standard JDBC SQLException.getMessage() to invoke a server-side stored procedure which retrieves the readable message text for the error.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: retrieveMessagesFromServerOnGetMessage

J2EEResourceProperty.description: The amount of time (in seconds) between automatic client reroute retries. This property is only used if the maxRetriesForClientReroute property is also set.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: retryIntervalForClientReroute

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Specifies the DRDA security mechanism. Possible values are: 3 (CLEAR_TEXT_PASSWORD_SECURITY), 4 (USER_ONLY_SECURITY), 7 (ENCRYPTED_PASSWORD_SECURITY), 9 (ENCRYPTED_USER_AND_PASSWORD_SECURITY), or 11 (KERBEROS_SECURITY). Plesae refer to DB2 manual for the constant value. If this property is specified, the specified security mechanism is the only mechanism that is used. If no value is specified for this property, 3 is used.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: securityMechanism

J2EEResourceProperty.description: The TCP/IP address or host name for the DRDA server. If custom property driverType is set to 4, this property is required.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: serverName

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Sets the time zone at session level on the server.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: sessionTimeZone

J2EEResourceProperty.description: JDBC driver property: sqljCloseStmtsWithOpenResultSet
J2EEResourceProperty.name: sqljCloseStmtsWithOpenResultSet

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Specifies whether the IBM DB2 Driver for JDBC and SQLJ allows using and loading of SQLJ profiles with the same Java name in multiple J2EE application (.ear) files.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: sqljEnableClassLoaderSpecificProfiles

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Specifies whether the IBM Data Server Driver for JDBC and SQLJ removes trailing zeroes when it retrieves data from a DECFLOAT, DECIMAL, or NUMERIC column as a java.math.BigDecimal object.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: stripTrailingZerosForDecimalNumbers

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Use the time remaining (if any) in a JTA transaction as the default query timeout for SQL statements. This feature depends on JDBC driver and database support for java.sql.Statement.setQueryTimeout. For DB2 type 2 on z/OS, the following data source properties impact support for query timeout: interruptProcessingMode, queryTimeoutInterruptProcessingMode. Refer to the JDBC driver documentation for more information.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: syncQueryTimeoutWithTransactionTimeout

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Specifies the level at which the IBM Data Server Driver for JDBC and SQLJ creates a java.util.Timer object for waiting for query execution to time out.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: timerLevelForQueryTimeOut

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Specifies the directory where the trace file will be created.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: traceDirectory

J2EEResourceProperty.description: The trace file to store the trace output. If you specify the trace file, the DB2 Jcc trace will be logged in this trace file. If this property is not specified and the WAS.database trace group is enabled, then both WebSphere trace and DB2 trace will be logged into the WebSphere trace file.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: traceFile

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Specifies whether to append to or overwrite the file that is specified by the traceFile property. The default is false, which means that the file that is specified by the traceFile property is overwritten.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: traceFileAppend

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Specifies the maximum number of trace files, for circular tracing.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: traceFileCount

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Specifies the maximum size of each trace file, for circular tracing.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: traceFileSize

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Specifies the level of trace, determined by a bitwise combination of constants: TRACE_NONE=0, TRACE_CONNECTION_CALLS=1, TRACE_STATEMENT_CALLS=2, TRACE_RESULT_SET_CALLS=4, TRACE_DRIVER_CONFIGURATION=16, TRACE_CONNECTS=32, TRACE_DRDA_FLOWS=64, TRACE_RESULT_SET_META_DATA=128, TRACE_PARAMETER_META_DATA=256, TRACE_DIAGNOSTICS=512, TRACE_SQLJ=1024, TRACE_META_CALLS=8192, TRACE_DATASOURCE_CALLS=16384, TRACE_LARGE_OBJECT_CALLS=32768, TRACE_SYSTEM_MONITOR=131072, TRACE_TRACEPOINTS=262144, TRACE_ALL=-1.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: traceLevel

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Specifies whether sequential tracing or circular tracing is done.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: traceOption

J2EEResourceProperty.description: JDBC driver property: translateForBitData
J2EEResourceProperty.name: translateForBitData

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Used with testConnection only. When set to true, clientRerouteServerListJNDIName will be unbound from JNDI name space when performing testConnection.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: unbindClientRerouteListFromJndi

J2EEResourceProperty.description: JDBC driver property: updateCountForBatch
J2EEResourceProperty.name: updateCountForBatch

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Specifies whether the IBM Data Server Driver for JDBC and SQLJ uses only the SQL built-in function IDENTITY_VAL_LOCAL to determine automatically generated key values.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: useIdentityValLocalForAutoGeneratedKeys

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Configure this property if your backend uses the Database Partitioning Feature (DPF) and your partitioning key remains constant throughout a transaction
J2EEResourceProperty.name: useTransactionRedirect

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Overlays existing entries in the error map by invoking DataStoreHelper.setUserDefinedMap. The userDefinedErrorMap can be used to add, change, or remove entries from the error map. Entries are delimited by ; (semicolon). Each entry consists of a key and value, where the key is an error code (numeric value) or SQLState (text enclosed in double quotes). Keys and values are are separated by = (equals sign). For example, to remove the mapping of SQLState S1000, add a mapping of error code 1062 to DuplicateKeyException, and add a mapping of SQLState 08004 to StaleConnectionException, the following can be specified for userDefinedErrorMap: "S1000"=;1062=com.ibm.websphere.ce.cm.DuplicateKeyException;"08004"=com.ibm.websphere.ce.cm.StaleConnectionException
J2EEResourceProperty.name: userDefinedErrorMap

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Setting this flag to true will cause to WebSphere Application Server to validate connections when they first get created and to keep trying to get a good connection from the database if the validation fails. Setting this flag to false prevents any additional validation from being performed - newly created connections are assumed to be valid and usable.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: validateNewConnection

J2EEResourceProperty.description: This is useful only if validateNewConnection flag is true. This property controls how many times WebSphere will try to get a connection from the database before giving up
J2EEResourceProperty.name: validateNewConnectionRetryCount

J2EEResourceProperty.description: This is useful only if validateNewConnection flag is true. This property controls the interval between retries to retrieve a connection from the database. Unit is seconds
J2EEResourceProperty.name: validateNewConnectionRetryInterval

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Specifies a default transaction isolation level for new connections. Resource References and Access Intents override this value. To configure a default transaction isolation level, use the constants defined by JDBC: 1 (READ UNCOMMITTED), 2 (READ COMMITTED), 4 (REPEATABLE READ), 8 (SERIALIZABLE).
J2EEResourceProperty.name: webSphereDefaultIsolationLevel

J2EEResourceProperty.description: Sets a default query timeout, which is the number of seconds (0 means infinite) that a SQL statement may execute before timing out. This default value is overridden during a JTA transaction if custom property syncQueryTimeoutWithTransactionTimeout is enabled. This feature depends on JDBC driver and database support for java.sql.Statement.setQueryTimeout. For DB2 type 2 on z/OS, the following data source properties impact support for query timeout: interruptProcessingMode, queryTimeoutInterruptProcessingMode. Refer to the JDBC driver documentation for more information.
J2EEResourceProperty.name: webSphereDefaultQueryTimeout
